<biogHist>
<abstract>In Need of Care is a phrase that was used to describe children who lacked sufficient care or could not be cared for effectively. In early legislation this term was not used specifically. Instead children were classified as being destitute, neglected, uncontrollable or incorrigible. In need of care was sometimes abbreviated on child welfare records as INOC or INC. (The acronym INC is also used for Intensive Neighbourhood Care.)</abstract>
<p>From 1895 to 1971, children in need of care and children who had committed offences were dealt with under the same legislation. From 1972-1979 children in need of care were covered separately under the Community Welfare Act. In 1979 the Children's Protection and Young Offenders Act again combined the legislation into one Act. In 1993 they were again dealt with separately with the passing of the Children's Protection Act.</p>

</biogHist>
</description>
